SYMPTOM_TEXT: The first shot I received on December 28th.  I have fatigue and a headache for about three days and my arm did hurt for close to 2 1/2 weeks,  the second week it was red, 3 inches in diameter, raised, also it itched very badly for 4-5 days.                I received the second maderna vaccine on 1/28/21 about 5:45 pm. I had noted about 8 pm mild burning to the lower part of my legs and bottom of my feet that evening.  Later I started to have mild nausea about 9 pm, but it resolved, and I went to bed.  I woke up about 3:11 with diarrhea and my body and mainly "my skin" started to hurt, as if someone was taking a wire brush to my legs, and slowly pulling out each hair, but at one time. After another hour or so, I started to have severe chills with increased nausea and more severe severe body/bone/joint pains. I took Tylenol at this time. I noted that the bottom of my ribs or rib cage hurt with breathing, also I had upper abdominal pain, severe lower back pain and a headache. The next morning I stayed in bed all day and took a few baths, I had multiple episodes of diarrhea. I was nauseated, but no vomiting.  I still had chills, bodily shaking, fatigue, muscle and joint pain.  I tried to sleep off and on through the day.  That evening I did have a temperature of 101.4 with using Tylenol and Motrin.  It did come down later that evening, but I still had severe pain of my body and my skin hurt, even the hair on my head, during the night about 2:45 am I took a bath and that did help with my body.  on Saturday evening I was able to start getting up and moving around, but a severe decreased appetite. I've noted a drastic change in taste since having the vaccine and have lost 9 lbs in the past week.  I am able to taste, but everything has a different taste.  I have had two covid tests PCR's in order to return to work.  I also have had the continued bilateral leg burning from the calves to the bottom of my feet.  The sensation is if you are cold outside and come back in and run your hands or feet under warm water to warm them up and that pain you feel when they warm up is how they feel, but on a milder level than that pain.  I also have had post nasal drip that has started in past 5 days and while at work in the ER on Tuesday I had a PA look at my ears and I had a large amount of fluid behind both ears.  I had a zpack that I had at the pharmacy that I had refilled and have taken that for the past four days with some relief.  I still feel fluid in my ears, but mildly better.  The headache and fatigue is getting better each day.  My appetite is still very diminished as well as how things taste in my mouth, it is way different than anything I have ever experienced before.  I also had an Issue on Monday 2/1/21 when I was working, I felt in my brain, as if it was just not as sharp, cloudy. I had an issue with typing on my right hand for a few hours (upper row on rt side) that has since resolved, but it was a truly "off" day.  It has taken me this entire week to start to feel even a bit more back to human.  So what remains- the bilateral leg to bottom of feet weird burning sensation, decreased appetite,  taste alterations, post nasal congestion with bilateral fluid in ears, shortness of breath with activity, mild burning in lungs with activity (working out/running in the cold weather).           this was just a side note that was copied to the bottom.       I was unable to touch my arm right arm due to swelling and pain for about three day, which I know is to be expected and actually wasn't as sore as long as the first shot.  I did take a few doses of Motrin 800mg but tried to stay with Tylenol and Zofran, and hydrate.              I noted that warm baths helped the most and the use of a heating pad on my lower back and an ice pack on and off my head for the headaches.   Thank you

Patient sat in exam room for 10 minutes after receiving vaccines and then parent requested to move to chairs in hallway prior to leaving for final 5 minutes. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient complained of dizziness and said she was going to pass out. Observation nurse called site clinical lead over, at that time the patient was  responding to verbal cues. Mask was taken down and she was guided to  take slow deep breaths, continued to report feeling as though she was going to pass out. Site clinical lead then noted patient with fixed gaze to the size, clenching hands and rigid posture. Observation nurse called for EMS assistance. Patient breathing slowed, mouth open, eyes remain fixed to the size with rigid posture for 5-10 seconds. Patient did not respond to any verbal cues. Site clinical lead and observation nurse  lowered patient to the floor, at which point patient became responsive. Responded correctly to reason for visit to site, location and how she was feeling. Denied history of seizures or stroke. Reported feeling anxious and needing to use the bathroom. Did not appear to lose bowel control at any point.  Patient was very diaphoretic and pale, but alert overall. Cold compresses applied to forehead and back of neck while patient remained supine. EMS arrived and had patient sit up, at which point she again became very pale and reported feeling as through she was going to pass out. EMS transported to hospital for further evaluation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient arrived for 2nd dose of Pfizer Covid 19 vaccine but did not return with his vaccination card.  Registration staff looked up 1st dose information and wrote Pfizer and the lot number on line 1 which created a new card for him.  Then, inadvertently placed a Moderna sticker on the card to send back to the nurses for administration.  Nurses at vaccine table verified patient and stated they would be administering moderna but no rejections were made from patient and nurse continue with administration.  Patient was in our recovery area when another staff member let me know of the error and I immediately went to check on him for any adverse reactions and explained the situation to him.  Patient was apologetic for the mistake of not bringing his card.  I made patient aware this was not his fault and that staffing should have caught the mishap.  I explained to him that he would need to wait 30min and I would contact my site provider for instruction and call if follow up was needed.  Obtained name, DOB and phone number.  Patient left the area with no complaints and no adverse signs or symptoms.  Once I spoke with site provider, I was instructed to let the patient know he did not need a repeat vaccination at this time.   I then called patient and made aware no further action needed at this time.  Instructed patient to call his primary care physician if any symptoms arose post vaccination or with any questions/concerns may contact our vaccine area.

Felt suddenly faint. Have hx of vasovagal syncopy and when I faint my blood pressure goes very, very  LOW. I moved to a armchair near the window thinking if I fainted I would not fall on floor and I mentioned to a nurse that I was feeling off and have a hx of vasovagal syncopy and if my BP dropped very low to not worry, I'm fine and it will readjust. They sent medic over and took BP which was 200/120. I have NO hx of high blood pressure. He took it repeatedly and it remained at least 200/120 and he wanted me to get it checked out so I was taken by ambulance to hospital. Pressure normalized a short time later w no intervention. Purchased good BP cuff and that night BP was average 118/84 and now 99/68 (it tends to run low to normal in general)
LAB_DATA: EKG and blood work. They would not give me copy of EKG nor let me see report. She said was ok. Basic CBC labs normal re heart though  slightly elevated hematocrit and hemoglobin. BP since then has been low to normal as usual.  Not sure whether I'd consider this a life threatening risk and can't say for sure whether it was the vaccine but thought I should mention it. Have not seen any other similar adverse reaction reported.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: -Approximately one hour after receiving the 2nd dose of the Moderna Covid vaccine on 2/3/21, I noticed a  heat wave kind of sensation from my back , up through the back of my head, and very mild dizziness. -Between 3:00 and 4:00 pm I noticed I was becoming very tired, and having some difficulty concentrating  and recalling information. I noticed my arm had started to become mildly achy, and body was beginning to ache mildly as well. -About 7:45 pm I was experiencing significant fatigue and "brain fog" during conversation with my son. Stopped in the middle of things and went to bed, needing to hold handrail to walk upstairs due to extreme fatigue and mild dizziness. -Between 3:00 and 4:00 am I woke up thinking I was feeling vibration of loud sound - but it was heart rate of 150 bpm. Temperature was 102 F.  Chest was heavy and tight.  8/10  pain with head ache and body ache.  Heart rate remained high for at least 15 minutes, so my husband took me to the Emergency Department. They ran EKG, took labs, and chest x-ray. My heart rate started to come down during this time. I was told there were no problematic findings. My heart rate was between 100-106 by the time I left. Fever had come down to about 100.  Began to get extreme nausea - was given Zofran. -In bed the entire day 2/4/21.  -2/5/21, continued to experience mild to moderate fatigue and brain fog, difficulty with recall and new learning. Had to leave work early. Continued same symptoms throughout evening, able to sleep in segments. -2/6/21: As of today, I am continuing to experience fatigue and some brain fog, for example, I wrote down my only son's birthday incorrectly. This is not remotely normal.
LAB_DATA: EKG, chest x-ray, lab draw - did not receive printout of the results from the Emergency Department upon discharge. Was told there were no abnormal findings.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the second dose on Tuesday and on Thursday morning I woke with 2 lesions that were painful on my left side of my tongue and a maculopapular rash on bilateral legs, chest and left arm. By Friday the lesions on the tongue were mostly resolved and the rash on my body was beginning to clear - it was less red and there were fewer lesions. However, Friday late afternoon I began to notice pain and burning just above my gluteal fold on the right buttock and was able to see a crescent shaped lesion that was very red, raised and extremely painful in a burning way.  This was first seen in spite of discomfort a couple of hours earlier (I was at work) around 6:30 PM. By 10:00 PM I began to notice the same burning sensation very suddenly and in the same location on the right buttock and was able to find another lesion identical to the first on that side.
LAB_DATA: I went to the local ED concerned for this being an allergic skin reaction from the vaccine at at the ED they drew a tryptase level, and gave initial doses of prednisone, benadryl and zantac. They then prescribed a tapering dose of prednisone, a regular dose of famotidine 40 mg daily and encouraged use of benadryl PRN. At this time I do not have a result for the tryptase level, as it is a send out test for our hospital. However, the rash continues to improve but the lesions on bilateral buttock are thus far unchanged, continue to be red, raised and painful, but there are no new lesions.
ALLERGIES: Zoloft, Paxil, gentamycin, morphine, dilaudid, codeine, hydrocodone

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Around 10:30 pm on 2/5/21, almost 6 hours after my first dose of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine, I started feeling fatigued, soreness in my arm and a metallic taste in my mouth developed. I took 2 Advil (400mg) around 12:30am.  By 1am, my left side was weak, mildly numb and the left side of my head and left foot were prickly. By 3am, my tongue and throat felt mildly numb and all the other symptoms continued.  My husband, who is an internist, gave me a Benadryl tablet at that time. On 2/6/21, I woke up fatigued and weak on my left side. The prickly feeling in my head and foot has gone away and replaced with a headache on the left side. I still feel weak and slightly numb on the left side and my tongue and mouth still feel a little numb as well. No breathing difficulties. I have never had a reaction to any vaccine and I don't have any food allergies. I am only allergic to cats and occasionally have seasonal allergies in the fall.

On January 18, two days after getting the first dose of the vaccine I woke up with a sense of fullness or pressure in my left ear, mild sinus congestion, and chills. The congestion and chills ended after one day, but the feeling of fullness in the ear has persisted to this day. Then, on January 29, I had a bout of positional vertigo and vomiting that lasted two to three hours. I also experienced ringing or roaring in my left ear. Ever since, I have a bout of vertigo approximately every 24 hours, and the ringing and sense of fullness in the ear ebb and flow on 24 hours cycles as well. This experience has been debilitating and affected my ability to work. My doctor has diagnosed Meniere's disease and says he has been seeing similar symptoms apparently linked to the COVID vaccines. I started taking prednisone on doctor's orders yesterday (February 5), which has stopped the vertigo. Ringing and occasional fullness in the ears persist.

Tuesday, 1/26/2021 - I was feeling exhausted and got out of breath with minimal exertion. Heart rate jumped up with minimal exertion (e.g. just standing, heart rate climbed about 110). I also started feeling dizzy and , ultimately, fainted, which put me in the emergency room, where they ruled out a PE and all cardiac emergencies. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got the first dose of the Moderna COVID-19 vaccine at 3pm 1/13/21. I was fine for the 30 minutes after, not even sore at the injection site.  Around 6pm, my muscles started aching, but not painful enough to be concerned.  At 3am 1/14/21, I woke up in pain in every muscle. Enough to wake me, but not terrible.  At 7am, I noticed a pinpoint pain in my armpit, and my muscles still ached.  At 9:30am, I took ibuprofen to attempt to curb the pain a bit.  Around 10am, it got so painful I was limping, and having trouble bending down or reaching above shoulder height.  At 11:30am, I noticed the pinpoint pain in my armpit had gotten worse, and there is a hard, approximately quarter-sized round lump in this spot. Very painful.  At 2:30, I went to move my shirt sleeve and the pain at the injection site was so intense I screamed when I touched it.  This pain continued until 1/16/21 when I woke up feeling entirely normal.  Since 1/16/2021, my hands have been randomly stiffening, either completely stretched out and dropping anything in them, or closing tight enough to leave fingernail marks on my palms. I will also reach to grab things and my hands will sometimes bend into odd shapes, instead of what I intended for them to do. This began at 1-2 times a day, and is becoming more often. It is now up to 2-4 times daily.
LAB_DATA: None so far, making doctor?s appointment with Dr. Monday morning. Dr. is not the physician that gave me this vaccine, I got it at work by a Pharmacy physician.

56 y.o. female with a history of a latex allergy, cancer and childhood asthma who received her second dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 mRNA vaccine and subsequently developed generalized pruritis five minutes after. She developed similar symptoms 6 hours after receiving the first dose, but this time was more severe. She arrived to the emergency department and after 15 minutes began to develop a cough, increased work of breathing, and voice changes. She received 0.3 mg epinephrine subcutaneously and albuterol nebulizers. Over her three hours in the department she received famotidine, 125mg methylprednisolone, diphenhydramine, an additional dose of epinephrine and 4x albuterol nebs. However, he dyspnea continued to return, and she was admitted. Improved overnight and was discharged HD2. widespread pruritis initially 5min post-Pfizer vaccination (2nd dose). Progressed to severe coughing, dyspnea requiring repeated doses of epinephrine and albuterol. Admitted to intermediate unit for further cares. Noted to have had mild delayed pruritis prior to first dose of pfizer vaccine.

73 y.o. female with a history of breast cancer, stroke, and hyperlipidemia who received her second dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine at an outside clinic. Within 10 minutes of receiving the vaccine she developed new numbness and swelling in her tongue, along with numbness in her extremities. She was given 0.3 mg epinephrine per protocol and was then advised to be seen in the emergency department. Her symptoms resolved once she arrived at the emergency department. She was observed for a period of two hours without worsening symptoms and was then discharged. presented to the ED following pfizer vaccine ingestion. received epinephrine IM prehospital for report of tongue swelling and and numbness at the time. She was improved at the time of presentation to the ED. Observed for several hours and discharged home without recrudescent sx. Although cannot find objective evidence of tongue swelling, administration of epi prehospital with report of improvement of symptoms is suggestive that this was a true anaphylactic reaction to the vaccine.

A couple that we know had the same experience but one was Moderna and one Phizer  In my case the reaction was later about 6pm and I had my shot at about 11am WED the same day. They had me sit in the holding area as they do for 15 minutes but they are more concerned about breathing issues. At 6pm I was a bit dizzy but it got worse. I was trying to look at my laptop and my eyes were dancing around the screen like a pin ball machine. I quickly gave up and figured I would watch TV HA HA jokes on me!  Same issue with the TV, so I closed my eyes and just listened for about an hour or so occasionally checking the TV but not acceptable for a couple hours before I could sit up. My arm Continually became more sore my the the minute and tender. I had absolutely no reaction early in the day aside from some minor pain as the day went on and expected.  I then tried to stand up about 7pm and WHOA I like to fall over I was so dizzy. I then had chills that faded in a hour or so. As it was getting close to bed time I knew there was no way I could make it to our 1st floor bedroom even if a friend assist me.  I asked her to go upstairs and get my old faithful walker from my 2016 escapades. I had balance issues back then from the sepsis and staph infection and everything else that was nothing like this. I was holding on to the walker for dear life and it was like someone was trying to throw me out of the walker, I'm wondering if it was a severe inner ear issue I suspect.  Off to sleep with no problem and later the next day I stared feeling better. I do have vertigo from time to time and took a pill but it was nothing like that. My greatest fear is what IF I were out in the car running an errand when all this took place. I checked this online but found nothing. There is a site you can post concerns over any abnormal symptom and I will report this on the CDC site as we should. They need to capture things like this with such short trials. Mine was the Moderna vaccine.
LAB_DATA: NA at this time. i will be asking my GP if he wants to see me.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: What I describe is not an adverse effect, but I am thinking it might be useful for you to know that I have an unexpected positive outcome that might be of use(?) to some of the long haulers who have been struggling with issues since getting covid19. After 2nd vaccine I have noticed that my legs are not so achey; indeed, they are much better.  It is very weird and so far so good.  Perhaps if the long haulers receive immunization, it will have some positive effect on their depressions, inflammations that are lingering.  I did not expect this good effect. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna shot #2: About 6-8 hours in, I got the expected serious joint aches, chills, headache, and fever (101F). This lasted for about 2 days, managed well by alternating Motrin and Tylenol. A mild rash occurred a few days after shot #2.   Thought I was done since most of my colleagues bounced back after 2-3 days. Then 48 hours in, I developed a racing heart (HR in the 110-120s), sweating palms/soles, tingling/numbness in the feet/arms, warm flushes over my chest, nausea, and a few loose stools. No position or relaxation method would resolve these symptoms. All I could do was lie down perfectly still with an ice pack on my forehead and hope this was short-lived and would pass. I could not sleep. I had no appetite. Over the 8 days this has been occurring, I lost 3 pounds.  I could not find any literature of anyone else having any cardiac/dysautonomia symptoms. It scared me. I have no prior cardiac history and no history of anxiety. I went to the ER. Labwork showed an elevated D-dimer (luckily the CT scan showed NO blood clots), elevated WBC/neutrophils, and low potassium. Thyroid labs (which I had tested a few days later) were normal. The ER assumed the abnormal labs were due to the immune response to the vaccine and referred me to a cardiologist.   I did a virtual visit with the cardiologist the next day. He suggested a heart monitor and scheduling an echo. The heart monitor was mailed to me. I started wearing it on 2/4/21 (3 days ago). I am supposed to wear it for 7 days and then mail it back. My echo is scheduled for 3/4/21. Again, I have had no previous cardiac history. I am an active, healthy 38 y/o F.   These symptoms (racing heart (HR in the 110-120s), sweating palms/soles, tingling/numbness in the feet/arms, warm flushes over my chest, nausea, and a few loose stools) have continued to last for another 8 days and are debilitating. I have not been able to work.   On day 7 of these symptoms, I called my PCP?s emergency line. They suggested calling the cardiologist to see if they would consider prescribing a beta blocker for symptomatic relief. I called the cardiologist last night. They prescribed Metoprolol. I haven?t taken it yet. It?s officially day 8. I thought I was in the clear and had not had symptoms since last night, but then just now another episode of these cardiac/dysautonomia symptoms have occurred but less intense than previously.   At this point, I have had had 10 days of symptoms post Moderna vaccine #2 but 8 of those days are specifally the cardiac/dysautonomia symptoms. Although a little better, these symptoms have NOT resolved and continue.  I realize I am probably an outlier in terms of how I have reacted to this vaccine. I would love a call back to know if other people have had a similar experience, so I can understand if this is ?normal.? I understand 7% of patients in the Moderna vaccine trial had ?symptoms? lasting longer than 7 days. Were they symptoms similar to mine? Will this go away completely? Any help is appreciated.   Of note, I did develop a nice rash below my injection site on Moderna shot #1. Does that mean I?m more ?reactogenic? and would potentially have a harder time with shot #2? Does size matter in how you will react? Moderna is 100 mcg (instead of Pfizer?s 30 mcg) I am petite (5?2? and am now 106 lbs since I?ve lost weight).
LAB_DATA: 1/31/21: Elevated D dimer (0.81), Elevated WBC (11.48)/neutrophil (8.76), Low Potassium (3.3), Low BUN (6), Low sodium (133) 1/31/21: CT of chest (normal, no blood clot)  2/3/21: TSH/Free T4 normal, TPO normal  2/4/21: Cardiac monitor placed (will wear for 7 days) 3/4/21: Echo scheduled
PRIOR_VAX: Pertussis component of TDAP (was told I had a reaction as a kid, not sure what reaction I had)

Recieved 2nd moderna dose 02/04/2021 in my left arm at 10 a.m. approx.  No symptoms besides a small headache throughout day.  At 10:15 that evening I started to become chilled.  By 11 p.m. I had uncontrollable shaking chills, accompanied by a fever of 101 and body aches.  By 1 a.m. I was still having uncontrollable shaking chills and severe body aches and  Body sweats.  I had a sweatshirt on over a tee shirt and a heating pad on between the two with two comforters on. At 3 a.m. I had to take ibuprofen (800 mg) because my body hurt too bad to even touch my skin.  My eyelids hurt.  My toes hurt. My ears hurt.  My fever was up to 103.  I fell asleep finally and woke up at 730 a.m. feeling much improved besides some mild chills.  I made the wrong decision to go to work.  I arrived at work at 830 and by 10 a.m. I started to get chilled again, achy and feeling like I was going downhill again.  I decided to go home.  By the time I got home at 11 I had chills again, fever of 101 and body hurt.  I slept until 3 p.m. at which time I woke up chilled and wanted to take a hot shower.  My other half noticed I had hives on my face (which I documented in photos).  I took a benadryl and went back to sleep.  Woke up again at 7 p.m. tried to eat something but had no interest and just wanted to sleep.  Throughout the night I would get the sweats that would drench through my t shirt.  The following day, 2 days post 2nd dose I slept all day.  Not as chilled but very tired.  Noticed injection site was now red and swollen, again documented in pictures.  Slept all day.  Today injection site has gotten slightly larger based on markers I marked on my skin, but not as red.  Not too energetic but much improved.

I was out of work for an entire week and not able to do anything for that entire timeframe.
